  "prompt": "How does international law intersect with national laws on money laundering?",
  "response": "International law intersects with national laws on money laundering in several key ways:\n\n1. International Frameworks and Conventions\n- United Nations Convention Against Transnational Organized Crime\n- Financial Action Task Force (FATF) recommendations\n- Basel Committee guidelines\n- Establish global standards and principles for combating money laundering\n\n2. Mutual Legal Assistance\n- Countries collaborate on investigations\n- Cross-border information sharing\n- Extradition of suspected money launderers\n- Coordinated legal enforcement efforts\n\n3. Regulatory Compliance Requirements\n- Know Your Customer (KYC) protocols\n- Suspicious transaction reporting\n- Customer due diligence standards\n- Uniform anti-money laundering (AML) guidelines\n\n4. Sanctions and Enforcement\n- International economic sanctions\n- Asset freezing mechanisms\n- Coordinated financial intelligence\n- Prosecution of transnational financial crimes\n\n5. Jurisdictional Cooperation\n- Harmonization of legal definitions\n- Consistent investigative procedures\n- Mutual recognition of legal proceedings\n- Standardized legal frameworks\n\nThese intersections help create a comprehensive global approach to preventing and detecting money laundering activities across different national legal systems.",
